\int_1^\infty\frac{\exp(-nx)}{x}dx
\int_1^\infty\frac{\exp(-nx)}{x}dx=n\int_ n^\infty\frac{\exp(-x)}{x}=nE_1(n)
\frac {e^{-n}} n> \int_1^\infty\frac{\exp(-nx)}{x}dx
\int_1^\infty\frac{\exp(-nx)}{x}dx<\int_1^\infty{\exp(-nx)}dx
\int_1^\infty\frac{\exp(-nx)}{x}dx>\sum_{k=1}^{\infty} \dfrac{\exp(-nk)(1-\exp(-n))}{n(k+1)}=\frac{\exp(-n)}{2n}+\mathcal{O}(1)\exp(-2n)
\begin{align}n \int_n^{\infty} dx \frac{e^{-x}}{x} &=e^{-n} - n \int_n^{\infty} dx \frac{e^{-x}}{x^2}\\&= e^{-n} -\frac{e^{-n}}{n} + 2 n \int_n^{\infty} dx \frac{e^{-x}}{x^3} \end{align}
n \int_n^{\infty} dx \frac{e^{-x}}{x} \sim e^{-n} \sum_{k=0}^{\infty} \frac{(-1)^k \, k!}{n^k} \quad (n \to \infty)
